Here is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line, counts the number of occurrences of a specific word, and writes the results to a new file.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <unordered_map>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("input.txt");
    std::ofstream output_file("output.txt");
    std::unordered_map<std::string, int> wordCount;

    // Read file line by line.
    while (file) {
        std::string line;
        std::getline(file, line);

        // Split the line into words.
        std::string word;
        std::istringstream iss(line);
        while (iss >> word) {
            wordCount[word]++;
        }
    }

    // Count the occurrences of each word.
    for (const auto& pair : wordCount) {
        for (const auto& count : pair.second) {
            output_file << pair.first << ": " << count << std::endl;
        }
    }

    // Clean up.
    file.close();
    output_file.close();

    return 0;
}
```

This program reads the input file line by line, counts the occurrences of each word in the file, and writes the results to the output file. The `unordered_map` is used to store the count of each word. Note that this program assumes that the input file is in a valid text format. It does not handle any errors that may occur during file I/O or counting.

